04899nam a22007215i 9780228010180DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280101807 a10.1515/97802280101802doi  a(DE-B1597)655470  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHF1040.9.C36bS64 2022 7aHIS0010102bisacsh04a330.967112231 aSneyd, Adam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCommodity Politics :bContesting Responsibility in Cameroon /cLauren Q. Sneyd, Charis Enns, Adam Sneyd, Steffi Hamann. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b12 diagrams, 5 maps, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables, Figures, and Maps -- tCommodities in the Global Arena: Whose Responsibility, Whose Agenda? -- tAcknowledgments -- tGlobal Commodity Politics, Africa, and Responsibility -- tSlick Perspectives: Analyzing Responsibility Pertaining to Commodities in CEMAC -- tApproaches to Responsibility in Cameroon: National Flash Points -- tGreasy Business: Perspectives on Responsibility in Cameroon’s Palm Oil Sector -- tCrude Commitments: Contending Perspectives on Responsibility along the Chad-Cameroon Pipeline -- tSugaring Up Responsibility: Sugar and Formal CSR in Cameroon -- tBittersweet Realities: Cocoa and Responsibility -- tResponsibility Politics in Comparative Perspective -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aResponsibility is political. As the international community has called for more responsible environmental, social, and governance performance, the politics of commodities has become more fraught. Commodity Politics cuts through the new rhetoric of responsibility and presents innovative research from Cameroon to provide a better understanding of the political complexity surrounding commodity production and trade in the twenty-first century.Assessing the perspectives of businesses, international organizations, governments, and civil society groups, the authors offer insights gleaned from years of field research in a commodity-dependent country. Commodity Politics presents case studies of sugar, palm oil, cocoa, and the Chad-Cameroon pipeline project. These cases uncover a problematic politics that is much broader than the implications of corporate social responsibility codes for people and the planet, delivering solid rationales for policy-makers and commodity stakeholders to think more deeply about investor-driven approaches to improving environmental, social, and governance conduct. This book trains students and scholars to better recognize political intricacies and consequential flash points.Immersing its readers in timely debates over the meaning and intent of responsibility, Commodity Politics breaks new ground in the political analysis of development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgriculturezCameroon. 0aCommercial productsxPolitical aspectszCameroon. 0aEconomic developmentzCameroon. 0aMineral industrieszCameroon. 0aResponsibilityxPolitical aspectszCameroon. 7aHISTORY / Africa / Central.2bisacsh  aCSR.  aCentral Africa.  aESG.  acocoa.  acommodities.  adevelopment.  aforeign investment.  agovernance.  apalm oil.  apipelines.  apower.  aresources.  asugar.  asustainability.1 aChérel-Robson, Milasoa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnns, Charis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGayi, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamann, Steffi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut4